               <p>De Koker was a Dutch physician, resident in <placeName>Rotterdam</placeName>, who
                  was part of a pietist group in <placeName>Rotterdam</placeName> (the Collegianten)
                  and associated with a Mennonite church. He hosted <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> when the latter traveled
                  through the <placeName>Netherlands</placeName> and <placeName>Germany</placeName>
                  to visit the Moravians in <date when="1738">1738</date>. The two struck up a
                  friendship and correspondence, and De Koker helped make some of <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s writings accessible in
                  the <placeName>Netherlands</placeName> by translating them into Dutch. See
                  Johannes Van Den Berg, <hi rend="italic"><persName><ref
                           target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>John Wesley</persName> and the
                     Netherlands</hi> (<placeName>Nashville</placeName>: Kingswood, <date
                     when="2002">2002</date>), 59â€“78.</p>
